1
00:00:06,640 --> 00:00:10,399
In this series we’ve talked quite 
a bit about goods and services.  

2
00:00:10,400 --> 00:00:14,160
Now it’s time to look at the people who 
produce all those goods and services.  

3
00:00:14,720 --> 00:00:20,400
These are people who perform labor, which means 
they must have a job. But how do we determine  

4
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:26,000
who has a “job” and who doesn’t? The answer is 
actually more complicated than one might think. 

5
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:32,960
Economists define the labor force as all 
nonmilitary people who are both employed  

6
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:38,480
and unemployed. However, different countries 
often define the labor force in different ways.  

7
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:44,320
In the United States, the Bureau of Labor 
Statistics determines how many people are  

8
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:51,120
in the labor force. They consider people to be 
employed if they are 16 years or older and meet at  

9
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:57,839
least one of the following requirements. One, they 
worked at least one hour for pay in the past week.  

10
00:00:58,720 --> 00:01:03,200
Two, they worked fifteen or more hours 
without pay in a family business.  

11
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:10,240
Or three, they held jobs but did not work due 
to either sickness, vacation, labor disputes,  

12
00:01:10,240 --> 00:01:15,679
or bad weather. Typically, those who are 
not included in the labor force include  

13
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:23,920
full-time students, stay-at-home parents, retired 
people, active military, the institutionalized,  

14
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:28,160
and those who have given up looking for 
employment for an extended period of time.  

15
00:01:29,920 --> 00:01:35,120
What if someone has more than one job? They’re 
still only counted once in the labor force. 

16
00:01:36,160 --> 00:01:41,759
Technology is constantly changing the labor 
force. In the early days of the United States,  

17
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:47,760
most citizens were farmers. Throughout the 
1800s, however, the economy transformed  

18
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:53,360
due to the Industrial Revolution, a time 
of rapid economic expansion caused by the  

19
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:58,880
shift from agriculture and production by hand 
to factories and production using machines.  

20
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:05,759
By the early 1900s, heavy manufacturing had 
become the main driver of the American economy.  

21
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:11,760
In the second half of the 1900s, a boom in 
electronics created a new wave of factory  

22
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:18,160
jobs. Beginning in the 1970s, the revolution 
in personal computers led to yet another boom.  

23
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:24,960
Due to rapidly changing technology, over the past 
few decades service-producing industries have  

24
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:32,240
been far outpacing good-producing industries.
Globalization has also dramatically changed  

25
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:37,760
the labor force in recent years. While the 
number of service jobs has increased, the  

26
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:44,720
United States has lost millions of manufacturing 
jobs, mostly due to outsourcing and offshoring.  

27
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:51,040
Outsourcing is when a company contracts with 
another company to do a specific job that would  

28
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:57,760
otherwise be done by a company’s own workers. Most 
companies outsource work in at least some way.  

29
00:02:58,480 --> 00:03:04,160
Offshoring is when a company shifts some of 
its operations, or resources of production,  

30
00:03:04,160 --> 00:03:10,799
to another country. More often than not, companies 
outsource and offshore in order to save money,  

31
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:15,040
as they can pay workers in other countries 
less than workers in their own country. 

32
00:03:15,920 --> 00:03:21,119
As less-skilled manufacturing jobs moved 
overseas, the Americans who had filled  

33
00:03:21,120 --> 00:03:27,040
these jobs had to find new work, and many had 
to go back to school or enter new job training  

34
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:32,480
programs in order to gain new skills. Because 
of this, it is increasingly the case that a high  

35
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:38,399
school diploma alone is not enough to prepare 
Americans for financial success. Therefore,  

36
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:43,600
post-secondary education has skyrocketed 
in popularity over the past few decades.  

37
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:48,960
Economists have two explanations for the 
connection between educational advancement  

38
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:55,120
and higher wages. The first theory, called the 
learning effect, says that education increases  

39
00:03:55,120 --> 00:04:00,560
efficiency of production, and therefore leads 
to higher wages. The second theory, called the  

40
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:05,920
screening effect, says that the completion 
of college signals to employers that a job  

41
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:12,000
applicant is both intelligent and hard-working.
Other trends in recent years include a shift  

42
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:18,720
toward a more diverse labor force, an increase 
in part time workers, and a shift toward what  

43
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:25,760
is known as a “gig economy.” A gig economy is 
a labor market characterized by freelance work,  

44
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:32,159
as opposed to permanent jobs. Instead of a worker 
staying with one company, in a gig economy that  

45
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:37,840
worker would have short-term contracts with 
various companies. Whatever career you decide on,  

46
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:43,760
you will have to be prepared for change, as labor 
markets are increasingly dynamic. At some point in  

47
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:49,520
your life, you will almost certainly be a part of 
the labor force, whether you want to be or not. So  

48
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:55,840
it’s best to be prepared in advance, which means 
we’d better continue to learn about economics.

